In an offline step, we split each text into sentences using rusenttokenize library, a rule -based  sentence segmenter for Russian (https://pypi.org/project/rusenttokenize).

For example, FOAF (http://xmlns.com/foaf/spec/ ) is the result of an early exemplication (1999) of a vocabulary for the Semantic Web, which did not emerge (did not intend to do so) from any standardisation or cognitive/formal analysis.

Other popular ontologies include DBpedia ( http://dbpedia.org/ontology/ ), the re- sult of collective cleaning of Wikipedia user-based template specications, and schema.org ( https://schema.org/ ), an output of an industrial standardisation body fostering search engine optimisation via semantics.
A community has emerged to integrate and support cognitive analysis by means of Ontology Design Patterns (ODP, http://www.ontologydesignpatterns.org ) [18,22,33].

4.1 Direct reuse of ontologies: the OpenCitations Data Model The OpenCitations Data Model (OCDM) [11] is based on the OpenCitations On- tology (OCO, https://w3id.org/oc/ontology ), which aggregates terms from existing well-known ontologies.

4.2 Hybrid reuse of ontologies and patterns: the ArCo ontologies ArCo (Architecture of Knowledge, https://w3id.org/arco ) is a project dedi- cated to the publication of the open knowledge graph (KG) of the Italian cul- tural heritage (CH) [7], deriving from the General Catalogue of Italian Cul- tural Heritage maintained by the Italian Institute of the General Catalogue and Documentation (ICCD).

The arco module (https://w3id.org/arco/ontology/arco/ ) is the root node of the network, addressing top-level distinctions and a general taxonomy, while the core mod- ule models general concepts, reused by the other modules (e.g.
Both ontologies and data are dis- tributed by ICCD ( https://github.com/ICCD-MiBACT/ArCo ) under a CC-BY 4.0 (Attribution-ShareAlike) license.
Overview of ArCo ontology reuse approaches Specically, ArCo directly reuses Cultural-ON ( http://dati.beniculturali.
it/cis/ ), and OntoPiA ( https://w3id.org/italia/onto/FULL/ ), a network of ontologies for top-level and cross-domain information.

Reused ODPs are annotated with the ontology design pattern annotation language OPLa (http://ontologydesignpatterns.org/opla/ ) which allows to express that new patterns are, for instance, a specialisation of existing patterns.

In response to the soaring needs of human mo bility data during the COVID - 19 pandemic, we extracted the worldwide daily population flows from billions of geotagged  tweets and SafeGraph data, and developed an interactive geospatial web portal, called ODT  (Origin -Destination -Time) Flow Explorer ( http://gis.cas.sc.edu/GeoAnalytics/od.html , Figure 1),  that allows researchers to query, aggregate, visualize, and download daily human movement data  at various geographic scales.

Extracting Human Mobility   We derived the human movement data in the format of origin -destination (OD) flows from two  data sources:  Worldwide geotagged tweets collected using the Twitter public API  (https://developer.twitter.com/en/docs/twitter -api); U.S. mobile device -based Social Distancing  Metrics provided by SafeGraph ( https://docs.safegraph.com/docs/social -distancing -metrics ).
The process  was performed using Apache Hive  (https://hive.apache.org)  coupled with Esri GIS tools for  Hadoop  (http://esri.github.io/gis -tools -for-hadoop)  on our Hadoop computing environment.

destination_cbgs  contains a list of key -value pairs with the key indicating  the destination census block group (from the origin census block group) and ‚Äúvalue is the number  of de vices with a home in census_block_group  that stopped in the given destination census block  group for >1 minute during the time period‚Äù (https://docs.safegraph.com/docs/social -distancing - metrics).
